definition.value: Deletion of 9p24.3 which can often result in some form of gonadal dysgenesis.
A disorder of the endocrine gonads.

A condition that results in a mild impairment of the cell's ability to respond to androgens. The degree of impairment is sufficient to impair spermatogenesis and/or the development of secondary sexual characteristics at puberty in males, but does not affect genital differentiation or development. Female genital and sexual development is not significantly affected by the insensitivity to androgens; as such, MAIS is only diagnosed in males.
Any of various intersex conditions determined principally by hormonal variations.
Any of various intersex conditions determined principally by anatomical variations.
A lack or shortage of a functional entity, by less than normal or necessary supply or function.
Deficiency of 5-alpha-reductase type 2 in genital tissues resulting in reduced local concentration of dihydrotestosterone (DHT).
Any of various intersex conditions determined principally by genetic variations.
Absence of an organ or tissue coupled with persistence of the organ/tissue primordium, which fails to develop completely.
A rare condition characterized by the absence of a vagina.
A syndrome characterized by the presence of uterine abnormalities.

Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome describes a spectrum of Mullerian duct anomalies characterized by congenital aplasia of the uterus and upper 2/3 of the vagina in otherwise phenotypically normal females. It can be classified as either MRKH syndrome type 1 (corresponding to isolated utero-vaginal aplasia) or MRKH syndrome type 2 (utero-vaginal aplasia associated with other malformations) (see these terms).
Failure of the cervix to develop.
A disorder which primarily affects a particular tissue or tissues.
A disorder which is trophic in nature; that is, it involves some issue with tissue growth.

An abnormal enlargement of the clitoris that is mostly congenital or acquired, though deliberately induced clitoris enlargement as a form of genital body modification is achieved through various uses of anabolic steroids, including testosterone.
Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal glands.
A type of adrenal hypoplasia with congenital onset.

A X-linked condition characterized by underdevelopment of the adrenal gland and adrenal insufficiency caused by mutation(s) in the NR0B1 gene, resulting in decreased activity of the nuclear receptor protein DAX1, which may be associated with hypogonadotropic hypogonadism.
Location of the urethral opening on the inferior aspect of the penis.
A severe form of hypospadias in which the urethral opening is located at the junction of the penis and scrotum.
Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the perineal region.
Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the scrotum.
A mild form of hypospadias in which the urethra opens just under the corona glandis.
The most common form of hypospadias, wherein the opening of the urethra is found near the head of the penis.
Location of the urethral opening on the penile mid-shaft.
Hypospadias in which the urethral opening is below its normal location in the glans.
Hypospadias in which the opening of the urethra is located on the head of the penis, but not at its tip.
Penile hypospadias which is inherited (familial), not acquired.
Hypospadias in which the location of the urethral opening is on the penile shaft.
Location of the urethral opening on the distal penile shaft.
Location of the urethral opening on the proximal penile shaft.
Hypospadias in which the opening of the urethra is located just below the head of the penis.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the penis.
Hypoplasia of the penis.
A penis at birth less than 2.0 to 2.5 cm in length, stretched from pubic tubercle to the tip of the penis).
A condition marked by the length of the penile being more than 2 standard deviations below the mean for age, accompanied by hypospadias.
A function of the urogenital system.
Any of various functions related to sexual activities or sex-related organs.
The processes of anatomical, psychological, and physiological changes related to sexual or reproductive functions during the life span of an animal, from fertilization to death.
The establishment of the sex of a female organism by physical differentiation.
An aspect of the process of sexual differentiation by which a potential female-specific structure, function, or behavior is changed by one of the processes of male development.
Although the term might seem to imply "removal" of female characteristics, in nearly all biological contexts it refers to prevention of an aspect of female development from manifesting.
The establishment of the sex of a male organism by physical differentiation.
Development of male sex characteristics based on drug presence in an organism's system.
Feminization of the testicles based on the inaction of androgens, and subsequent aromatization of testosterone into estrogen.
Note that, due to later work by Lawson Wilkins, a general shift in nomenclature occurred, resulting in "testicular feminization" because more often referred to as "androgen resistance".

Virilization induced by maternal use of androgens or high doses of certain weakly androgenic synthetic progestogens (progestins) structurally related to testosterone can masculinize (virilize) the external genitalia of a female fetus during susceptible times in pregnancy.
Any of various intersex conditions experienced by persons with a 46,XX karyotype.
Any of various intersex conditions experienced by persons with a 46,XY karyotype.
The state of a male whose body, especially the genitalia, shows evidence of below-normal prenatal (less commonly pubertal) androgen effects.

Historically, bisexual referred to attraction to persons of two gender identities, typically, but not always, defined as male and female. In modern use, it is usually used to refer to persons who are sexually and/or romantically attracted to persons with a gender or genders like theirs and those with a gender or genders unlike theirs.
Note that sometimes bisexual may be used as a synonym of pansexual.
